'''Vápenice''' ({{IPA-cs|ˈvaːpɛɲɪtsɛ}}) is a [[natural monument]] south-east of the village [[Slatinky]] in the [[Prostějov District]], the [[Czech Republic]]. It is a part of the [[nature park]] [[Velký Kosíř]].<ref name="Geological localities"/> The area is administered by the [[Nature Conservation Agency of the Czech Republic]] (''Agentura ochrany přírody a krajiny České republiky'').<ref name="AOPK"/>

Bedrock of Vápenice consists of Devonian [[Dolomite (rock)|dolomite]]s and the Lažánky [[limestone]], which are partly covered by Badenian (mid-[[Miocene]]) calcareous [[clay]]s and [[sand]]s.<ref name="Geological localities"/> This is the reason why the area has become an enclave<!--within what?--> of lime-tolerant ("[[Calcicole|calciphile]]") vegetation.<ref name="Natura2000"/>

The locality is protected because of the rare [[plant community]], especially hot dry ("xerothermic") [[grassland]]s, growing on terrain bumps, which are remnants of former minor limestone quarries<ref name="AOPK"/><ref name="CGS Olomouc"/> (which gave the place its [[Czech language|Czech]] name ''Vápenice''). Beside them there used to be a number of little fields<ref name="AOPK"/> and pastures for livestock.<ref name="CGS Olomouc"/> Some of the balks which used to separate the fields are preserved and help to prevent erosion. There are also some residues of [[orchard]]s in the northern part of the area.<ref name="AOPK"/>

[[File:Vapenice koniklec.JPG|left|thumb|[[Pulsatilla grandis|Greater Anemone]] growing at Vápenice]]
Steppe-like vegetation grows here mostly. The place is also valued for one of the richest populations of [[Pulsatilla grandis|Greater Anemone]] (''Pulsatilla grandis'') in [[Central Moravia]]; in the 2004 census 19,699 blooms were counted here. Other notable plants growing here are [[Anemone sylvestris|Snowdrop Anemone]] (''Anemone sylvestris''), [[Aster amellus|European Michaelmas Daisy]] (''Aster amellus''), [[Bupleurum falcatum|Sickle Hare's Ear]] (''Bupleurum falcatum''), [[Carex flacca|Blue Sedge]] (''Carex flacca''), [[Carex tomentosa|Downy-fruited Sedge]] (''Carex tomentosa''), ''[[Carex michelii]]'', [[Prunus fruticosa|European Dwarf Cherry]] (''Prunus fruticosa''), ''[[Dorycnium herbaceum]]'', [[Melampyrum arvense|Field Cow-wheat]] (''Melampyrum arvense''), [[Ononis spinosa|Spiny Restharrow]] (''Ononis spinosa''), [[Orchis militaris|Military Orchid]] (''Orchis militaris''), [[Orobanche elatior|Knapweed Broomrape]] (''Orobanche elatior''), ''[[Pilosella macrantha]]'', ''[[Primula veris]] subsp. canescens'', [[Scabiosa canescens|Fragrant Scabious]] (''Scabiosa canescens'') and ''[[Thesium dollineri]]''.<ref name="Natura2000"/> Bigger stones are covered by saxicolous [[lichen]]s, which are an important indicator of the level of air pollution.<ref name="AOPK"/> The grasslands need to be maintained and shrubs of [[Robinia pseudacacia|Black Locust]] (''Robinia pseudacacia''), [[Cornus sanguinea|Common Dogwood]] (''Cornus sanguinea'') and [[Ligustrum vulgare|European Privet]] (''Ligustrum vulgare'') have to be regularly removed here.<ref name="CGS Olomouc"/>

Weed vegetation of the ''[[Caucalidion lappulae]]'' alliance can be found at the edges of some surrounding fields, including rare species [[Adonis aestivalis|Summer Pheasant's-eye]] (''Adonis aestivalis''), [[Anagallis foemina|Poorman's Weatherglass]] (''Anagallis foemina''), ''[[Caucalis|Caucalis platycarpos]]'', [[Conringia orientalis|Hare's Ear Mustard]] (''Conringia orientalis''), [[Falcaria vulgaris|Longleaf]] (''Falcaria vulgaris'') and ''[[Thymelaea|Thymelaea passerina]]''.<ref name="Natura2000"/>

Vápenice is also important from an entomological point of view. There live a number of insects dependent on the local shrub-steppe grasslands.<ref name="Natura2000"/> Some of notable species which were observed here are for example [[European mantis|European Mantis]] (''Mantis religiosa'')<ref name="CGS Olomouc"/> and butterfly [[Euplagia quadripunctaria|Jersey Tiger]] (''Euplagia quadripunctaria'').<ref name="Natura2000"/>

The area of the locality is 0.19&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> and it lies 250–300 metres above sea level. It has been protected as a natural monument of the Czech Republic since 1&nbsp;November 1990, when its status was declared by the Regional Authority of the [[Olomouc Region]] (''Krajský úřad Olomouckého kraje''). The locality was also registered by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature|IUCN]] in the [[IUCN protected area categories|category]]&nbsp;IV (habitat management area)<ref name="AOPK"/> and together with other abandoned limestone quarries at the slopes of Velký Kosíř was included among the [[Natura&nbsp;2000]] sites under the name Kosíř&nbsp;– lomy (''Kosíř&nbsp;– quarries''), code CZ0714076.<ref name="EEA 1"/> One of the reasons for listing it is that the locality is valued as an important [[Orchidaceae|orchid]] site.<ref name="EEA 2"/>

